EXT. RURAL MAILBOX, NEBRASKA - DAY

A weathered hand puts a letter in a mailbox and raises the little
red flag. The envelope, handwritten: TRI-COUNTY FEED COOPERATIVE,
RE: PARTS.

EXT. RURAL MAILBOX, EAST TEXAS - DAY

Another mailbox, another envelope, another red flag up. A dog
watches from a porch.

EXT. MAILBOX ROW, SOUTH CAROLINA LOWCOUNTRY - DAY

A third. The mail carrier takes it without a glance, tosses it in
the tray between coupon packs.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Supper cleared to one side. Peg reads from a handwritten strip of
paper, glasses down her nose.

PEG:
Fourteen. Two. Nine.

Cricket thumbs a swollen 1971 Reader's Digest to page fourteen,
column two, counts nine words down, and writes one word on a pad.

PEG:
Six. One. Eleven.

He flips, counts, writes. Peg looks at the pad over his shoulder.

PEG:
That's a grocery list.

CRICKET:
This week it is.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN - NIGHT

Crate number one stands in a welding jig, half-skinned, purge lines
run neat along the frame rail where nobody will ever see them. TITO
welds, hood down, bead steady.

Around the shop, in ones and twos, MEN FROM BAY TWO work quiet
stations — machining, harness-lay, upholstery on a crash couch. A
chalkboard by the door tracks pickups in and out against feed-co-op
job tickets.

Tito lifts his hood, pulls a film camera from his toolbox, shoots
two frames of the crate, and winds the film down.

INT. TRI-COUNTY AUCTION BARN, ROOF - NIGHT

Joss, headlamp off, feeds a wire antenna from the roof peak toward
the dead flagpole by the gate, paying it out gloved hand over hand.
Below him, Gunny holds the ladder and points, twice, at where the
tie-off goes. Joss ties it off there.

INT. STITCH'S HANGAR, EAST TEXAS - NIGHT

A crop-duster hangar. Stitch at a workbench rig, two fingers on a
morse key, sending. A fly strip turns overhead.

INT. DUTCH'S BASEMENT, WISCONSIN - NIGHT

A ham station, everything labeled, everything square. Dutch sends,
pauses, logs the exchange in pencil in a columned notebook.

EXT. GUNNY'S PORCH, SOUTH CAROLINA - NIGHT

A key wired to a TV tray. Sweet tea. Gunny sends with one finger,
slow and exact, frogs loud in the dark past the porch rail.

INT. DAWES BARN - NIGHT

Cricket copies code off the air onto the pad, letter groups filling
line after line. He keys two clicks. Somewhere, two click back.

INT. DAWES FARMHOUSE, KITCHEN - NIGHT

Cricket raps the table edge with one knuckle: two, pause, two.

CRICKET:
All clear.

He raps three, evenly spaced.

CRICKET:
No. Stop. Trouble.

PEG:
And supper?

CRICKET:
There's no code for supper.

Peg raps the table twice, pause, twice — then once, hard, on the
sugar bowl lid.

PEG:
All clear, and there's pie.

Cricket looks at her a moment. Writes it on the pad.

EXT. DAWES BARN - LATER THAT NIGHT

The barn window lit. Inside, faint, morse ticking.

Peg crosses the yard in her house coat, stops at the barn wall,
raps it twice — pause — twice. Goes back to the house.

Inside the barn, without breaking his copy rhythm, Cricket reaches
up and flicks the work light off-on once.

CUT TO:
